      <center>
      <table border=0 cellpadding=3 cellspacing=0 width=475>
	    <tr>
         <td style="font-weight: bold; font-size: 10pt;" background="/images/bg_heading_blue_01.jpg"><center><b>The Phoenix Chronicles
: Strange Bedfellows
 by Eshkin of Prexus
</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
		 <td>                            
	                                   

<P>Cast out of Surefall Glade…</P><br><P>That night—the night of my exile-- I looked bitterly back at the torchlit tunnel that was the entrance to Surefall Glade. I had lived there all my life. All my life…</P><br><P>That was over now. That life was just a bright and painful memory. It was time for a new life.</P><br><P>For a time, I lived in the remote parts of Qeynos hills, hunting and foraging for my meals and camping against the cold. The quiet of the wilderness demanded nothing of my mind. I could try to forget. I could live as an animal.</P><br><P>This I did for two years.</P><br><P>Of course, during this time, I was not without certain needs. Clothing wears out, bowstrings break, and arrow points were always a commodity. For this reason I had to endure the presence of people from time to time and sell my pelts in Qeynos for money to purchase that which I needed.</P><br><P>The pallor of my mind and the heaviness of my heart must have been fading at last. On one of these excursions I found myself, on a lark, at Fish’s Tavern. After almost two years, Fish Ranamer still recognized me. We exchanged michevious grins, as he quietly changed my coin for a case of Blackburrow Stout. </P><br><P>The stout was a treat for me. Having finally packed the heavy crate back to my camp in the hills, I nursed the beers, on special occasions: Layla’s birthday, my own birthday, and sometimes when Tunare favored me with a quick and easy hunt</P><br><P>I had bought twenty-four beers from Fish Ranamer, each of the odd, brown clay bottles sealed in wax. After each beer I would carefully rinse the bottle and use it later to hold water.</P><br><P>Several months later, I was down to eight of them. </P><br><P>I had not been gone from camp long when a yearling buck crossed my path. With the day’s hunting done early, I decided to enjoy the last of the autumn warmth and simply lay by the stream with a beer.</P><br><P>At first I could not decide what was wrong when I opened the wooden case in my tent. I glanced about, listening and smelling the air. Someone had been in my tent. The crate was not latched, as it should have been. While I was out, someone had been in my camp.</P><br><P>Carefully, I unclasped the thong on my scabbard.</P><br><P>No sound. Not even the birds. </P><br><P>Whoever had been in the tent was still nearby.</P><br><P>Slowly, I emerged from the tent, looking about for my uninvited visitor.</P><br><P>He was sitting on the log I had felled next to my fire pit, as relaxed as though it were his own camp. It was a gnoll, the black of his fur was peppered with the white of age and his face was scarred from some long passed battle. He wore a leather tunic and breeches, and an axe hung from a thong at his belt.</P><br><P>A heavy, leather bag sat on the log beside him.</P><br><P>He had come silently, and invisibly. My pulse quickened and my hand fell to my sword.</P><br><P>He addressed me in broken common, "You…you like beerrr….?"</P><br><P>"Uh…I’m sorry…" I said.</P><br><P>His paw gestured toward the crate beside me, "Beerr! Beerr! You like?"</P><br><P>This was somewhat different from the greetings I had heard from other gnolls. "Uhh…yes. I like beer."</P><br><P>It grinned. The edges of its mouth turning up and wrinkling its snout—showing a rake of yellowed, broken canine teeth. Out of the bag, it produced a bottle. Deftly, he flipped the cap off of it with one thumb. "Good beerrr it is! Best beerr it is!" He took a long, sloppy swig, his tongue lapping it noisily out of the bottle as he poured it all over himself.</P><br><P>He was drunk! </P><DIR><br><DIR><br><br><P>A drunk gnoll in my camp?</P><br><P>"Uhh….yes, it is good beer. I really don’t like beer much but this is good beer. It’s uh…it’s gnoll beer…"</P><br><P>The gnoll slurped and lapped noisily as more beer slopped down the front of his tunic.</P><br><P>"…but I guess you know that."</P><br><P>The gnoll released a humungous belch. "Ahh…good gnoll beerrr! My beerr it is! Gnasher I am!"</P><br><P>Ahhh…So this was Gnasher Furgut, the gnoll brewer! Somehow I had envisioned him as a bit more, well…fearsome. Younger and more sober, perhaps. Antonius Bayle’s guards would like</P></DIR><br></DIR>         <br>
